@m-burst I know you explicitly addressed this in your original post, but I think it might be worth revisiting one of the assumptions -- is `allow_population_by_alias` really that problematic? I know the pydantic docs have a big red warning about it, but as long as your aliases are just camelcased versions of the attributes (and they have non-pathological names), I'm having a hard time imagining a real-world scenario where the potential collision would actually cause problems. (Maybe I'm not thinking hard enough?)

Personally, I use the following `APIModel` as a base class for any model interfacing with external clients:
```python
import re

def snake2camel(snake: str, start_lower: bool = False) -> str:
    camel = snake.title()
    camel = re.sub("([0-9A-Za-z])_(?=[0-9A-Z])", lambda m: m.group(1), camel)
    if start_lower:
        camel = re.sub("(^_*[A-Z])", lambda m: m.group(1).lower(), camel)
    return camel

class APIModel(BaseModel):
    class Config(BaseConfig):
        allow_population_by_alias = True

        @classmethod
        def get_field_schema(cls, name: str) -> Dict[str, str]:
            """
            Generate a camelCase alias
            """
            field_config = super().get_field_schema(name) or {}
            if "alias" not in field_config:
                field_config["alias"] = snake2camel(name, start_lower=True)
            return field_config
```
Relying on a generated alias means I can be confident I'm not accidentally/carelessly manually generating collisions, and so far I have never run into a situation where converting to camel case could introduce ambiguity.

Using the above model means the service is always interfacing externally in camelcase, but I can always use snake case when writing python. (I'm not bothered by the fact that external clients can choose to use snake case if they want to, but maybe I should be?)

Alternatively, here's a relatively concise implementation of the `make` classmethod as I interpreted your description, with the same API as the usual `__init__` (except using the python attribute names), and the same validation errors:
```python
class APIModel2(BaseModel):
    @classmethod
    def make(cls, **data: Any):
        instance = cls.construct(values=data, fields_set=set(data.keys()))
        return cls(**instance.dict(by_alias=True))
```
As long as your aliases and attribute names don't conflict, I think this would behave properly.

@m-burst no I'm not suggesting two models.

I'm suggesting with have 3 alias options on a field:
* `alias` used for loading and dumping
* `load_alias` only used for loading, takes preference over `alias`
* `dump_alias` only used for dumping (`.dict()` and `.json()`), takes preference over `alias`

@dmontagu I agree about `allow_population_by_alias`, I think we should removing that warning or stop it being a warning, I think it unnecessarily upsets people.

I think the warning on `allow_population_by_alias` is fair because loading external data should be as strict as possible.

Suppose I have a RESTful API endpoint where clients JSON data in the body. If I enable `allow_population_by_alias`, clients using my API will be able to send requests that are incorrect (i.e. do not conform to schema) but will be processed correctly, and neither the clients nor I will know that there is a mistake. And in this situation I won't be able to disable `allow_population_by_alias` ever because technically it can break the clients (and I may want to disable it at any time because the reasons I enabled it are purely internal to the backend).

@dmontagu The idea of `APIModel2` is exactly what I was looking for, though there is obviously a lot of room for performance optimization, and I just thought it made sense to have a built-in and more optimized implementation of this in pydantic itself.

@samuelcolvin I still don't understand how load/dump aliases are the answer to my question. To put it simply, I need to construct the same model with and without aliases while specifying explicitly what the keys are, and I don't see how load/dump aliases will allow me to do everything I need in one model.
